  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Uncertainty-Aware Adaptive Curriculum Learning for Non-Autoregressive Translation' (UACL-NAT), which redefines how bilingual knowledge is progressively acquired in NAT models by introducing a self-monitoring, dynamic curriculum driven by multi-granular uncertainty estimation. While existing methods apply fixed-stage curricula or uniform distillation, UACL-NAT posits that optimal learning occurs when the model advances from word-level to sentence-level knowledge only when it has sufficiently mastered the current level—measured through both representational fidelity and predictive confidence. Our framework operates in three synergistic components: (1) Multi-Granular Uncertainty Estimation Module: At each training step, the student computes epistemic uncertainty (via Monte Carlo dropout) and representation divergence (via KL between teacher-student attention maps) at token, phrase, and sentence levels. These uncertainties are combined into a Granularity Readiness Score (GRS) per level. (2) Adaptive Curriculum Controller (ACC): A lightweight LSTM-based meta-controller observes historical GRS trends and decides which granularity-specific distillation loss to emphasize in the next batch—e.g., if token-level uncertainty drops below threshold, phrase-level KD is activated. This replaces rigid scheduling with data-driven progression. (3) Uncertainty-Weighted Cross-Lingual Span Alignment: Building on Paper 2, we enhance phrase-level grounding by using mBERT-augmented GCNs to align multilingual spans, but now weight these alignments by local uncertainty—high-uncertainty regions receive stronger GCN regularization to stabilize learning. Additionally, we introduce Layer-wise Granularity Gates: trainable sigmoid units at each Transformer layer that modulate the strength of incoming distillation gradients based on the layer’s current alignment with its designated granularity (e.g., early layers suppress sentence-level gradients). This enables emergent layer specialization without architectural constraints. The full system is trained end-to-end with a dual objective: translation accuracy and curriculum efficiency (minimizing time-to-mastery). By making the curriculum responsive to the student’s internal state, UACL-NAT prevents overfitting to misleading teacher signals and reduces error accumulation in low-resource or morphologically rich languages. We expect significant gains in robustness, especially for long-tail vocabulary and syntactically divergent language pairs. Beyond NAT, this paradigm introduces a new class of self-paced, introspective learning systems applicable to any knowledge distillation scenario where teacher-student capacity gaps exist.",
